Quiz 2¶

Formerly quiz 3

Your second quiz asks you to put some of your newly acquired methods of text analysis into action.

Your assignment is as follows:

  1. Pick ONE of either TF-IDF, topic modeling, or word2vec, and apply that method to the corpus which the code cells just below will allow you to access: it's a corpus of approximately 150,000 Yelp reviews of restaurants, which I pulled out of the Yelp Open Dataset.

  2. Upon completing the task above, answer the four questions at the bottom of the notebook. Just a few sentences is fine for each.

Process:

Please make a copy of this notebook, inserting your code where specified and inserting any additional cells as you see fit.

Please be sure to at least minimally comment your code so that the grader can follow along!

Please upload your completed notebook to the assignment page on Canvas.

Step 0. Load in the data¶

Run the two cells below to get the data for this quiz imported into your Colab workspace.

This will result in local directory (folder) called "reviews" that should serve as your base directory for any future operations. (The equivalent of the "wheel-clean" directory we've used in the past).

In [1]:
# Load in the data 

# For downloading large files from Google Drive
import gdown

# Then download the zip file
gdown.download('https://drive.google.com/uc?export=download&id=1BfOVtHxeFZxdSjGhhyu3dy4eUCfS4BmI', quiet=False)

In [4]:
# for file i/o
import os

base_dir = "reviews/" 

all_docs = [] # our list which will store the text of each doc; empty for now

docs = os.listdir(base_dir) # get a list of all the files in the directory

for doc in docs: # iterate through the docs
    if not doc.startswith('.'): # get only the .txt files
        with open(base_dir + doc, "r", encoding="utf-8") as file: # force unicode conversion to keep PCs happy
            text = file.read() # read in the file as a single text string
            all_docs.append(text) # append it to the all_docs list

# lastly, just check the length of all_docs to see if it's 4008
len(all_docs)
Out[4]:
41012
In [5]:
# need our handy nltk tokenizer 
tokenizer = TreebankWordTokenizer()

# and we'll get titles
directory = base_dir # as defined above
files = glob.glob(f"{directory}/*.txt") # different way of getting the list of filenames from above, but same thing
wheel_titles = [Path(file).stem for file in files] # the Path library lets you pull out the name of a file, minus the file extension

# and the function
def make_sentences(list_txt):
    all_txt = []
    counter = 0
    for txt in list_txt:
        lower_txt = txt.lower()
        sentences = sent_tokenize(lower_txt)
        sentences = [tokenizer.tokenize(sent) for sent in sentences]
        all_txt += sentences
        print(wheel_titles[counter]) # let's print the title of the article
        print("Sentences: " + str(len(sentences)))  # let's check how many sentences there are per article
        counter += 1
    return all_txt

# let's train our model!
reviews = gensim.models.Word2Vec(
    sentences,
    min_count=2, # default is 5; this trims the corpus for words only used once; 
    size=100, # size of NN layers; default is 100; higher for larger corpora
    # vector_size=100,    # if you are getting an error while running this on your own computer, try this param insted 
    workers=5) # parallel processing; needs Cython

print("Owner and woman similarity:" ,reviews.wv.similarity(w1="owner",w2="woman"))

Question 1. Generally speaking, what did you learn about your dataset from the modeling approach that you chose?

From the modeling approach I used, I learned that this dataset is relatively biased when it comes to race. For example, when I searched up Top 10 words similar to 'ethnic' majority of the words that were pulled up asian ethnicities, but none were from Europe, few were from South America and Africa. I was also surprised to see that "cook" and "chef" were not that similar to each other (.32).

Question 2. Are there any improvements and/or modifications you might make to your approach if you were to try to get better/more interesting results?

I think that it would be interesting to dive deeper into specific ethnic groups to see how they relate to each profession in a restaurant (ie how does Egyptian vs Italian compare with chef). Further, I think exploring different genders with restaurant profession would be interesting too (however, nonbinary is not in the reviews dataset vocabulary). I would have liked to see how nonbinary is similar to owner or chef (like I did with man and woman).

Question 3. Improvements notwithstanding, what is one specific interesting thing that you found?

I found it interesting to see how "Chinese" and "American" is similar to the word "tasty". "Chinese" is negatively similar to "tasty" at -.0016 and "American" is .18 similar to "tasty".

Question 4. What is a research question you might ask that is prompted by this finding, or by your modeling approach in general?

A research question I am wondering about is why specifically "Chinese" is negatively related to "tasty" and why "American" is more similar to "tasty". I wonder if it is because people don't use the word "tasty" along with "Chinese" when they leave reviews at restaurants (could it be that people use "tasty" with "American" restaurants more?). I feel like there could be many factors as to why the word "Chinese" and "tasty" are negatively similar, and I would like to research this more.
